{{italic title}} '''''Masques''''', L. 105, is a piece for solo piano by [[Claude Debussy]]. Composed in July 1904, it was premiered on 18 February 1905 by [[Ricardo ViÃ±es]] at the [[Salle Pleyel]] in Paris. Its sombre character reflects Debussyâs difficult separation from Lilly Texier, his first wife. The title refers to the [[commedia dellâarte]], although Debussy confided to [[Marguerite Long]] that the piece was "not Italian comedy, but an expression of the tragedy of existence" - (''"ce n'est pas la comÃ©die italienne, mais l'expression tragique de lâexistence."'')<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gerstle|first1=C. Andrew|last2=Milner|first2=Anthony Crothers|title=Recovering the Orient: Artists, Scholars, Appropriations|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9783718656875|page=79|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=16Kgk5EhPC4C&pg=PA79|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Tranchefort|first1=FranÃ§ois-RenÃ©| authorlink = FranÃ§ois-RenÃ© Tranchefort | title=Guide de la musique de piano et de clavecin|publisher=[[Fayard]]|isbn=9782213641126|page=428|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eruRBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT428|language=fr}}</ref> == Structure == * TrÃ¨s vif et fantasque (Ã 6/8) - CÃ©dez un peu (en sol bÃ©mol majeur) - Tempo I
